---
// src/pages/credentials/oem-parts.astro
// OEM Parts credential page — E-E-A-T trust signal
// Angle: OEM = manufacturer specs + warranty protection + no repeat failures
// Honest: aftermarket available on request if client wants to reduce cost

import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = "OEM Parts Appliance Repair | Original Manufacturer Parts | Los Angeles";
const description = "Same-day repair uses OEM (Original Equipment Manufacturer) parts by default. Manufacturer specs, warranty compliance, no repeat failures.";
const phone = "(424) 325-0520";
const phoneRaw = "4243250520";
const schemaJsons = [
  `{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "LocalBusiness",
  "name": "Same Day Appliance Repair",
  "telephone": "(424) 325-0520",
  "url": "https://samedayappliance.repair/credentials/oem-parts-appliance-repair/"
  }`,
  `{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is an OEM part?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "OEM stands for Original Equipment Manufacturer. An OEM part is made by the same manufacturer that produced the original component in your appliance — or by a supplier holding a licensed manufacturing contract with that brand. It's the exact part the appliance was designed and tested with: same materials, same tolerances, same electrical specifications. OEM parts are distinct from aftermarket parts, which are produced by third parties without a licensing agreement and may differ in materials, tolerances, or performance."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why does it matter whether the repair uses OEM or aftermarket parts?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "OEM parts are manufactured to the exact specifications the appliance was designed around. An aftermarket control board, heating element, or compressor relay may fit physically but operate outside the voltage, amperage, or thermal tolerances the appliance expects — causing the new part to fail prematurely or affect other components. For smart appliances with digital control systems, aftermarket parts can also create firmware compatibility issues. For appliances still under manufacturer warranty, an aftermarket repair may void the remaining warranty coverage."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does using OEM parts affect my appliance warranty?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Using OEM parts preserves compatibility with the manufacturer's warranty terms. If your appliance is still under a manufacturer's limited warranty that covers parts, the use of non-OEM components during a repair can void that coverage — the manufacturer's position is typically that repairs must use parts meeting their specifications. OEM parts, by definition, meet those specifications. If your appliance is out of warranty, this is less of a concern, though OEM parts still provide better reliability and fit."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I request aftermarket parts to reduce the repair cost?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Our default is OEM parts, but if cost is a priority for you, we can source aftermarket alternatives on request. We'll tell you upfront what the quality difference is for the specific part in question — some aftermarket parts for older or discontinued appliances are a reasonable choice, while others are not. We give you the information and let you decide. Our warranty on the repair covers the workmanship regardless of part type, though part warranties may differ."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Are OEM parts harder to get or more expensive?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For most major appliance brands — LG, Samsung, Whirlpool, GE, Sub-Zero, Bosch, Miele — OEM parts are readily available through authorized distributors. The price premium over aftermarket is real but usually modest relative to the total repair cost. For high-end brands like Sub-Zero, Wolf, or Miele, OEM is essentially the only sensible choice — these appliances operate at tighter tolerances and the cost of a failed aftermarket part often exceeds the savings."
      }
    }
  ]
}`
];
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>

  <Fragment slot="head-scripts">
    {schemaJsons.map((s) => (
      <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={s}></script>
    ))}
  </Fragment>

<style>
  :root { --red: #C8102E; --black: #0a0a0a; --gray: #f5f5f5; --border: #e2e2e2; --text: #1a1a1a; --muted: #6b6b6b; }
  .hero { background: var(--black); color: #fff; padding: 80px 24px 64px; text-align: center; }
  .hero-eyebrow { display: inline-block; background: var(--red); color: #fff; font-size: 0.78rem; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; padding: 5px 14px; border-radius: 3px; margin-bottom: 20px; }
  .hero-sub { font-size: 1.1rem; color: #ccc; max-width: 640px; margin: 0 auto 32px; line-height: 1.6; }
  .cta-row { display: flex; gap: 14px; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .btn-primary { background: var(--red); color: #fff; padding: 16px 34px; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; text-decoration: none; }
  .btn-secondary { background: transparent; color: #fff; padding: 16px 34px; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: none; border: 2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.35); }
  .hero-meta { margin-top: 28px; color: #aaa; font-size: 0.9rem; display: flex; gap: 24px; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .trust-bar { background: var(--red); padding: 18px 24px; }
  .trust-inner { max-width: 1100px; margin: 0 auto; display: flex; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 10px 32px; }
  .trust-item { color: #fff; font-size: 0.88rem; font-weight: 600; }
  .section { padding: 64px 24px; }
  .section-gray { background: var(--gray); }
  .section-black { background: var(--black); color: #fff; }
  .container { max-width: 1100px; margin: 0 auto; }
  .section-number { font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--red); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  h2.section-title { font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 3vw, 2.1rem); font-weight: 800; margin: 0 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  .section-black h2.section-title { color: #fff; }
  .intro-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 320px; gap: 48px; align-items: start; }
  @media (max-width: 768px) { .intro-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
  .intro-body p { margin: 0 0 18px; font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--text); }
  /* Sticky CTA */
  .sticky-cta { position: sticky; top: 24px; background: var(--black); border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px 24px; color: #fff; text-align: center; }
  .sticky-cta .cta-label { font-size: 0.75rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: #aaa; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .sticky-cta .cta-phone { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; text-decoration: none; display: block; margin-bottom: 12px; }
  .sticky-cta .btn-cta { display: block; background: var(--red); color: #fff; padding: 14px; border-radius: 5px; font-weight: 700; text-decoration: none; font-size: 0.95rem; margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .sticky-cta .cta-sub { font-size: 0.82rem; color: #888; }
  .cta-divider { border: none; border-top: 1px solid #222; margin: 18px 0; }
  .cta-detail { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; }
  .cta-detail li { margin-bottom: 6px; padding-left: 18px; position: relative; font-size: 0.85rem; color: #aaa; }
  .cta-detail li::before { content: "✓"; position: absolute; left: 0; color: var(--red); font-weight: 700; }
  /* Compare OEM vs Aftermarket */
  .compare-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 28px; }
  .compare-table th { padding: 13px 16px; text-align: left; font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; border-bottom: 2px solid #1a1a1a; color: #555; background: #050505; }
  .compare-table th:first-child { width: 38%; }
  .compare-table td { padding: 14px 16px; font-size: 0.9rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #1a1a1a; vertical-align: top; color: #888; }
  .compare-table tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
  .compare-table .row-label { color: #fff; font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.88rem; }
  .compare-table .oem { color: #50c060; }
  .compare-table .aftermarket { color: #c07030; }
  .compare-table .detail { font-size: 0.8rem; color: #555; margin-top: 3px; line-height: 1.4; }
  /* Why OEM cards */
  .reason-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 20px; margin-top: 32px; }
  .reason-card { background: #fff; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px; padding: 22px 20px; }
  .reason-icon { font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .reason-card h3 { font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text); margin: 0 0 8px; }
  .reason-card p { font-size: 0.87rem; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.65; margin: 0; }
  /* Brand notes */
  .brand-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(240px, 1fr)); gap: 16px; margin-top: 28px; }
  .brand-card { background: #111; border: 1px solid #1a1a1a; border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 16px; }
  .brand-card h3 { font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 700; color: #fff; margin: 0 0 6px; }
  .brand-card p { font-size: 0.83rem; color: #555; line-height: 1.55; margin: 0; }
  .brand-tag { display: inline-block; font-size: 0.7rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 3px; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .tag-critical { background: rgba(200,16,46,0.15); color: var(--red); }
  .tag-standard { background: #1a1a1a; color: #555; }
  /* Honest block */
  .honest-block { background: #fff; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-left: 4px solid var(--red); border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; padding: 22px 22px; margin-top: 28px; }
  .honest-block .h-label { font-size: 0.72rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.12em; color: var(--red); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .honest-block h3 { font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 0 0 10px; color: var(--text); }
  .honest-block p { font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.7; margin: 0 0 10px; }
  .honest-block p:last-child { margin: 0; }
  /* Credentials nav */
  .creds-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(190px, 1fr)); gap: 14px; margin-top: 28px; }
  .cred-card { background: #fff; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 16px; text-decoration: none; display: block; }
  .cred-card:hover { border-color: var(--red); }
  .cred-card .cred-icon { font-size: 1.4rem; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .cred-card h3 { font-size: 0.88rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text); margin: 0 0 4px; }
  .cred-card p { font-size: 0.78rem; color: var(--muted); margin: 0; line-height: 1.4; }
  /* FAQ */
  .faq-list { margin-top: 36px; }
  .faq-item { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); padding: 20px 0; }
  .faq-item:first-child { border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .faq-item h3 { font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text); margin: 0 0 10px; }
  .faq-item p { font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.7; margin: 0; }
  .nearby-links { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 10px; margin-top: 24px; }
  .nearby-links a { background: #fff; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 4px; padding: 8px 16px; font-size: 0.87rem; color: var(--text); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 500; }
  .nearby-links a:hover { border-color: var(--red); color: var(--red); }
  .bottom-cta { background: var(--black); color: #fff; padding: 64px 24px; text-align: center; }
  .bottom-cta h2 { font-size: clamp(1.6rem, 3vw, 2.2rem); font-weight: 800; margin: 0 0 16px; }
  .bottom-cta p { color: #aaa; margin: 0 0 32px; font-size: 1.05rem; }
</style>

<!-- HERO -->
<section class="hero">
  <div class="hero-eyebrow">Original Equipment Manufacturer Parts · Manufacturer Specifications</div>
  <h1>OEM Parts by Default — Because the Repair Should Last</h1>
  <p class="hero-sub">Every repair we do uses Original Equipment Manufacturer parts unless you specifically request otherwise. The part that goes in is the same spec as the part that came out — same tolerances, same materials, same fit for the appliance it's going into.</p>
  <div class="cta-row">
    <a href={`tel:${phoneRaw}`} class="btn-primary">Call {phone}</a>
    <a href="/book" class="btn-secondary">Schedule Service</a>
  </div>
  <div class="hero-meta">
    <span>🔩 OEM Parts Standard</span>
    <span>📋 Manufacturer Specifications</span>
    <span>🛡 Warranty Compliant</span>
    <span>🔁 Aftermarket on Request</span>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- TRUST BAR -->
<div class="trust-bar">
  <div class="trust-inner">
    <span class="trust-item">🔩 OEM Parts by Default</span>
    <span class="trust-item">📋 BHGS Registered #A49573</span>
    <span class="trust-item">🛡 GL + Workers Comp</span>
    <span class="trust-item">⭐ BBB Accredited A+</span>
    <span class="trust-item">🔬 EPA-608 Certified</span>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01 — Our Parts Policy</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">OEM is the default — not the premium option</h2>

        <p>When a part needs replacing, the default is always OEM — the original manufacturer part or a licensed equivalent built to the same specification. This isn't a premium tier. It's just how we do repairs. An aftermarket control board that runs 10% outside the design voltage range will fail again in 6–18 months. That's a callback we don't want and a repair you don't want to pay for twice.</p>

        <p>For high-end appliances — Sub-Zero, Wolf, Miele, Thermador, Bosch — OEM is the only sensible choice. These brands engineer their components to tighter tolerances than standard appliances. A Sub-Zero refrigerator with an aftermarket compressor relay isn't a Sub-Zero repair. It's a generic repair in a Sub-Zero cabinet.</p>

        <p>That said: cost is a real consideration. If you're looking at a 12-year-old dryer and the OEM heating element costs $180 versus an aftermarket part at $45, that's a conversation worth having. We source aftermarket parts on request, tell you exactly what the quality difference is for that specific component, and let you decide. We don't make the choice for you without asking.</p>

        <div class="honest-block">
          <div class="h-label">📋 Our Parts Policy — Written Plainly</div>
          <h3>OEM by default. Aftermarket by request only.</h3>
          <p>We stock and source OEM parts through authorized distributors for all major brands. If an OEM part is unavailable (discontinued models, long lead times), we tell you before ordering anything. Aftermarket alternatives are available on client request — we explain the trade-off for the specific part, you decide.</p>
          <p>Our 90-day warranty on repairs covers workmanship regardless of part type. Part warranties themselves vary: OEM parts typically carry manufacturer warranties; aftermarket part warranties depend on the supplier.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="sticky-cta">
        <div class="cta-label">Schedule Service</div>
        <a href={`tel:${phoneRaw}`} class="cta-phone">{phone}</a>
        <a href={`tel:${phoneRaw}`} class="btn-cta">Call Now</a>
        <a href="/book" class="btn-cta" style="background:#222; margin-top:-4px;">Schedule Online</a>
        <div class="cta-sub">OEM parts · $89 diagnostic waived with repair</div>
        <hr class="cta-divider" />
        <ul class="cta-detail">
          <li>OEM parts by default</li>
          <li>Aftermarket on request (cost savings)</li>
          <li>Authorized OEM distributors</li>
          <li>90-day workmanship warranty</li>
          <li>BHGS Registration #A49573</li>
          <li>BBB Accredited A+</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- OEM vs AFTERMARKET TABLE -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — OEM vs Aftermarket — What Actually Differs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Where the difference matters and where it doesn't</h2>

    <table class="compare-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Factor</th>
          <th>OEM Parts</th>
          <th>Aftermarket Parts</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td class="row-label">Manufacturing specs</td>
          <td class="oem">✓ Exact manufacturer tolerances
            <div class="detail">Same materials, voltages, thermal ratings as original</div>
          </td>
          <td class="aftermarket">Varies by supplier
            <div class="detail">May meet spec, may not — no standardized testing requirement</div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="row-label">Firmware compatibility</td>
          <td class="oem">✓ Guaranteed compatible
            <div class="detail">Critical for smart appliances with digital control boards</div>
          </td>
          <td class="aftermarket">Potential compatibility issues
            <div class="detail">Control boards and sensors can fail to communicate correctly</div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="row-label">Manufacturer warranty</td>
          <td class="oem">✓ Preserves coverage
            <div class="detail">Meets manufacturer's specification requirements</div>
          </td>
          <td class="aftermarket">May void remaining warranty
            <div class="detail">Manufacturer can deny coverage if non-spec parts were used</div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="row-label">Part lifespan</td>
          <td class="oem">✓ Designed for the appliance
            <div class="detail">Engineered to the same lifespan as the original component</div>
          </td>
          <td class="aftermarket">Often shorter
            <div class="detail">Lower-grade materials common in budget aftermarket parts</div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="row-label">Cost</td>
          <td>Higher upfront
            <div class="detail" style="color:#555;">Premium over aftermarket — usually modest relative to total repair</div>
          </td>
          <td>Lower upfront
            <div class="detail" style="color:#555;">Savings can be significant for older appliances with cheap parts available</div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="row-label">Our default</td>
          <td class="oem">✓ Yes — used unless you request otherwise</td>
          <td class="aftermarket">Available on request only
            <div class="detail">We explain the specific trade-off for the part in question</div>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- WHY OEM -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Why OEM by Default</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The practical reasons behind the policy</h2>

    <div class="reason-grid">
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-icon">🔁</div>
        <h3>No repeat failures</h3>
        <p>The most common cause of a repair failing within a year is a part that was slightly outside spec for the appliance it went into. Running a heating element at the wrong resistance, or a motor at the wrong amperage draw, shortens the component life predictably. OEM parts eliminate this variable.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-icon">📱</div>
        <h3>Smart appliance compatibility</h3>
        <p>Modern refrigerators, dishwashers, and washing machines communicate between components digitally. A control board that doesn't match the exact firmware version the appliance expects can cause error codes, failed cycles, or component shutdowns — even if the board is physically identical. OEM parts carry the correct firmware.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-icon">📋</div>
        <h3>Warranty protection</h3>
        <p>If your appliance still has manufacturer warranty coverage on parts, non-OEM repairs can void that coverage. The manufacturer's definition of a valid repair typically requires parts meeting their specifications. OEM, by definition, meets them. Aftermarket, by definition, may not.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-icon">🏷️</div>
        <h3>Luxury brands demand it</h3>
        <p>Sub-Zero, Wolf, Miele, Thermador, Gaggenau — these brands are engineered to tolerances that aftermarket parts typically don't meet. A $15,000 built-in refrigerator with a $40 aftermarket compressor relay is a false economy. For these brands especially, OEM isn't a preference, it's a requirement for the repair to hold.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-icon">🤝</div>
        <h3>Our warranty is cleaner</h3>
        <p>Our 90-day workmanship warranty is straightforward with OEM parts — we know the part performs to spec because it was built to spec. Aftermarket parts introduce a variable we don't fully control. When the repair is done right with the right part, the warranty means something.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="reason-card">
        <div class="reason-icon">📦</div>
        <h3>Parts availability</h3>
        <p>We source OEM parts through authorized distributors with established supply chains. For most major brands — LG, Samsung, Whirlpool, GE, Bosch, Miele — standard OEM parts are in stock or available within 1–2 days. We don't compromise on parts because of sourcing convenience.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- BRAND-SPECIFIC NOTES -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Brand-Specific Part Considerations</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Where OEM matters most — by appliance brand</h2>

    <div class="brand-grid">
      <div class="brand-card">
        <div class="brand-tag tag-critical">OEM Critical</div>
        <h3>Sub-Zero / Wolf</h3>
        <p>Dual-compressor systems, proprietary sealed system components, vacuum insulation panels. No acceptable aftermarket equivalent exists for most Sub-Zero sealed system parts. OEM only.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="brand-card">
        <div class="brand-tag tag-critical">OEM Critical</div>
        <h3>Miele</h3>
        <p>German-engineered to very tight tolerances. Control electronics are firmware-paired with specific hardware versions. Aftermarket control boards frequently cause error loops on Miele dishwashers and washing machines.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="brand-card">
        <div class="brand-tag tag-critical">OEM Critical</div>
        <h3>Thermador / Bosch</h3>
        <p>BSH Group products (Thermador, Bosch, Gaggenau) share component families. OEM sourcing through BSH authorized distributors is standard. Control board firmware versions are model-specific.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="brand-card">
        <div class="brand-tag tag-standard">OEM Standard</div>
        <h3>LG / Samsung</h3>
        <p>Large OEM parts networks with good availability. Inverter compressor technology in newer models requires exact spec matching. Smart diagnostics features may not function with non-OEM boards.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="brand-card">
        <div class="brand-tag tag-standard">OEM Standard</div>
        <h3>Whirlpool / GE / Maytag</h3>
        <p>Broad OEM parts availability through established US distribution networks. Aftermarket options exist for older models — worth discussing on a case-by-case basis for appliances over 10 years old.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="brand-card">
        <div class="brand-tag tag-standard">OEM Standard</div>
        <h3>Electrolux / Fisher & Paykel</h3>
        <p>OEM parts available through authorized channels. European-spec components require exact voltage and thermal rating matches. Aftermarket availability is limited for many models, making OEM the practical default anyway.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CREDENTIALS NAV -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05 — Our Full Credentials</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">OEM parts alongside a complete credential stack</h2>
    <div class="creds-grid">
      <a href="/credentials/licensed-appliance-repair/" class="cred-card">
        <div class="cred-icon">📋</div>
        <h3>BHGS Registered</h3>
        <p>California #A49573 — verifiable at bhgs.dca.ca.gov</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/credentials/insured-appliance-repair/" class="cred-card">
        <div class="cred-icon">🛡</div>
        <h3>Fully Insured</h3>
        <p>GL, Workers Comp, Commercial Auto.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/credentials/background-checked-appliance-repair/" class="cred-card">
        <div class="cred-icon">✅</div>
        <h3>Background Checked</h3>
        <p>All technicians individually screened.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/credentials/epa-certified-appliance-repair/" class="cred-card">
        <div class="cred-icon">🔬</div>
        <h3>EPA-608 Universal</h3>
        <p>Federal refrigerant certification.</p>
